19/07/2024, 10:49 - Varnit Verma: #include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <unordered_set>

using namespace std;

void dfs(int node, int parent, vector<vector<int>>& adj, vector<int>& values, vector<unordered_map<int, int>>& subtreeFreq, vector<int>& goodEdges, int k) {
    unordered_map<int, int> freq;
    freq[values[node - 1]]++;
    
    for (int neighbor : adj[node]) {
        if (neighbor == parent) continue;
        dfs(neighbor, node, adj, values, subtreeFreq, goodEdges, k);
        for (auto& p : subtreeFreq[neighbor]) {
            freq[p.first] += p.second;
        }
    }
    
    subtreeFreq[node] = freq;
    
    if (parent != -1) { // only check for non-root nodes
        bool isGood = true;
        for (auto& p : freq) {
            if (p.second > k) {
                isGood = false;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (isGood) {
            goodEdges.push_back(node);
        }
    }
}

int countGoodEdges(int n, int k, vector<int>& values, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
    vector<vector<int>> adj(n + 1); 
    for (const auto& edge : edges) {
        int u = edge[0], v = edge[1];
        adj[u].push_back(v);
        adj[v].push_back(u);
    }

    vector<unordered_map<int, int>> subtreeFreq(n + 1);
    vector<int> goodEdges;
    
    dfs(1, -1, adj, values, subtreeFreq, goodEdges, k);

    return goodEdges.size();
}

10/11/2024, 12:52 - Sheil DTU: Respected Sir,

I hope this message finds you well. I am writing on behalf of the students who have enrolled in the electives Data Structures (CO201) and Object-Oriented Programming (CO203). We would like to bring to your attention a scheduling conflict in the upcoming end-semester examination dates.

Currently, the exams for CO201 and CO203 are scheduled on 19th November and 21st November, respectively. However, our core subject exams are slated for 20th November and 22nd November, resulting in four consecutive days of exams without any breaks. This tight schedule puts us under considerable pressure and impacts our ability to prepare effectively.

We have noted that other electives under slots E1 and E3 are scheduled for 29th November and 4th December, respectively. We kindly request that the exams for CO201 and CO203 be rescheduled to these dates, or any other suitable dates that would provide a break between exams. This adjustment would ensure a fair opportunity for all students to perform to the best of their abilities.

Thank you very much for considering our request. We would be grateful if you could review the exam schedule and make the necessary adjustments.

Notice
Date: 18 November 2024

Subject: Postponement of Examination

This is to inform all students that the upcoming examination scheduled earlier has been postponed to 5th December 2024 due to the high Air Quality Index (AQI) levels in Delhi, which pose health risks.

The revised timetable and further updates will be shared soon. Students are advised to use this additional time for preparation and to take necessary precautions for their health.

For any queries, please contact the Examination Office.

Issued by:
Examination Department
Delhi Technological University

04/03/2025, 01:23 - Pratham P Dtu: Factors Affecting the Selection of Welding Electrodes

The selection of a welding electrode is crucial to achieving a strong, high-quality weld. The right electrode depends on multiple factors, including base metal type, welding position, current type, mechanical properties, and environmental conditions. Below is a detailed explanation of the key factors influencing electrode selection.


---

1. Type of Base Metal

The electrode material must match the composition of the base metal for proper fusion and strength.

For carbon steel, mild steel electrodes like E6013, E6010, E7018 are commonly used.

For stainless steel, electrodes such as E308, E309, E316 are selected.

For aluminum, tungsten or special aluminum electrodes are used (e.g., E4045).

Dissimilar metals require special electrodes like E309L (stainless to carbon steel).


✔ Matching the electrode with the base metal ensures proper bonding, strength, and corrosion resistance.


---

2. Welding Position

Different electrodes are designed for specific positions: flat, horizontal, vertical, and overhead.

All-position electrodes (e.g., E6010, E6011) are used in applications requiring out-of-position welding.

Flat and horizontal electrodes (e.g., E7024) allow faster deposition in controlled positions.


✔ Choosing the right electrode for the welding position ensures ease of use and prevents defects like sagging or incomplete fusion.


---

3. Type of Welding Current (AC or DC)

Some electrodes work with DC (Direct Current) only, while others work with AC (Alternating Current) or both.

E6010 → Only for DC+ polarity (deep penetration).

E6011 → Works with AC or DC (versatile, deep penetration).

E7018 → Works with AC or DC+, producing a low-hydrogen weld.


✔ Selecting an electrode compatible with the power source ensures arc stability and proper penetration.


---

4. Mechanical Properties Required (Strength, Ductility, Toughness)

Different welding applications require different mechanical properties.

Tensile strength: Higher strength applications (e.g., structural welding) require E7018 (70,000 psi tensile strength).

Impact resistance: Cold-weather welding (e.g., bridges, pipelines) requires impact-resistant electrodes.

Ductility & Toughness: Low-alloy electrodes like E7018 provide toughness for critical welds.


✔ Matching the mechanical properties to the application ensures strong, reliable welds.


---

5. Welding Speed & Deposition Rate

Fast-freezing electrodes (e.g., E6010, E6011) solidify quickly and are used for root passes.

Fast-fill electrodes (e.g., E7024) provide a high deposition rate for flat and horizontal welding.

Low-hydrogen electrodes (e.g., E7018) offer a balance between strength and deposition rate.


✔ Selecting an electrode with the right deposition characteristics improves productivity and efficiency.


---

6. Joint Design & Thickness of Base Metal

Thin metals require low-penetration electrodes like E6013 to avoid burn-through.

Thick metals need deep-penetration electrodes like E6010, E7018.

Gaps and poor fit-up require electrodes with good gap-bridging ability (e.g., E6011).


✔ Matching electrode penetration to material thickness ensures a strong, defect-free weld.


---

7. Environmental Conditions (Moisture, Temperature, Corrosion Resistance)

Moisture-sensitive environments require low-hydrogen electrodes (e.g., E7018) to prevent hydrogen cracking.

Outdoor welding (e.g., pipelines, field repairs) benefits from E6010, E6011, which work well in windy conditions.

Corrosive environments (marine, chemical industries) require stainless steel or special coated electrodes.


✔ Choosing an electrode suited for the environment prevents weld failures due to moisture absorption or corrosion.


---

8. Code and Specification Requirements

Industries like construction, aerospace, shipbuilding, and pipelines follow welding codes (AWS, ASME, ISO).

Codes specify the required electrode type based on strength, impact resistance, and application.


✔ Following industry standards ensures compliance with safety and structural integrity requirements.


---

Electrode Selection Chart (Common Types and Applications)


---

Conclusion

Selecting the right electrode is critical for weld quality, strength, and efficiency. Factors like base metal type, welding position, current type, mechanical properties, joint thickness, and environmental conditions must be carefully considered. Using the correct electrode ensures strong, defect-free welds that meet industry standards.

Bada maja aaya😄🤭
Aap sabhi ko aprilfull ki hardik subhkamnye..

Dear Students,
The *Department of Training & Placement, DTU*, is organising a session titled "*Campus Career Compass: Navigator to Your Professional Journey*" aimed at guiding students through various career options and identifying the skills required for the upcoming placement and internship season.

📌 *This session is mandatory for all 2nd and 3rd year students.*

🗓 Date: *14th May 2025(Wednesday)*
🕐 Time: 01:00 PM onwards
📍 Venue: B.R. Auditorium, DTU

The session will cover:
🔹 Essential strategies for placements & internships
🔹 Preparation tips for interviews and aptitude tests
🔹 Insights from industry experts to help you navigate the placement process effectively

📣 Your active participation is crucial to gaining valuable knowledge and preparing for future opportunities!

📝 Students who have an examination at the time of the session must submit valid proof of their examination using the following link:
https://forms.gle/LcR2ePq3HmeoB6kx6

⚠️ *Note: Strict actions will be taken against students who fail to attend the session without a legitimate reason.*

Regards,
Prof. Anil Singh Parihar
Head, Training and Placements
Delhi Technological University
